      <!-- Intro -->
      <div class="prose-dark">
        <h2 id="the-pipeline" class="anchor-top">The GEO Pipeline</h2>
        <p>
          <strong>Generative engine optimisation works by aligning your content with a sequential machine pipeline — not by improving a single ranking signal.</strong> When a user submits a query to Google AI Overviews, Perplexity, or ChatGPT, the system does not consult a ranked list of pages and display the top result. It executes a structured process: discover and index your content, retrieve documents relevant to the query, synthesise a response using a large language model, and decide which sources to credit. Your content either passes or fails at each stage independently.
        </p>
        <p>
          This pipeline model is the foundational insight that distinguishes <a href="/generative-engine-optimisation/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">generative engine optimisation</a> from traditional SEO. SEO optimises for a weighted combination of ranking signals that produce a position on a results page. GEO optimises for sequential eligibility across four distinct stages, each with its own criteria. Understanding where your content falls short at each stage — and what to do about it — is the complete theory of GEO in practice.
        </p>
        <p>
          For the broader definition and context of the discipline, see our <a href="/generative-engine-optimisation/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">complete GEO guide</a>. For a related breakdown of how answer engines specifically process queries, see <a href="/geo-explained/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">GEO explained</a>.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Pipeline Stages Table -->
