        <table class="w-full text-sm">
          <thead>
            <tr class="border-b hair bg-white/[.03]">
              <th scope="col" class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-white">Stage</th>
              <th scope="col" class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-white">What Happens</th>
              <th scope="col" class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-white">Primary Selection Signal</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody class="divide-y divide-[var(--line)]">
            <tr class="transition hover:bg-white/[.02]">
              <td class="px-4 py-3 font-semibold text-white">1. Crawl &amp; Index</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300">AI crawlers discover, fetch, and store your content in the retrieval index</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300">Robots.txt permissions, llms.txt signals, crawl budget, page accessibility</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="transition hover:bg-white/[.02]">
              <td class="px-4 py-3 font-semibold text-white">2. Semantic Retrieval</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300">Engine selects candidate documents using vector and keyword matching</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300">Topical authority, semantic relevance, entity clarity, site architecture</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="transition hover:bg-white/[.02]">
              <td class="px-4 py-3 font-semibold text-white">3. LLM Synthesis</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300">LLM extracts passages and assembles a coherent generated answer</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300">Extractable passage structure, declarative statements, format matching</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="transition hover:bg-white/[.02]">
              <td class="px-4 py-3 font-semibold text-white">4. Citation Selection</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300">Model assigns source attribution to the generated response</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300">Entity authority, schema signals, recency, unique data contribution</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <!-- Stage 1 -->
      <div class="prose-dark mt-16">
        <h2 id="stage-1-crawl" class="anchor-top">Stage 1: Crawl &amp; Index</h2>
        <p>
          <strong>Before any generative engine can cite your content, its crawlers must have discovered, fetched, and stored it in a retrievable index — and many brands inadvertently block this from happening.</strong> The crawl and index stage is the entry gate for GEO. A page that does not exist in the retrieval index cannot enter the pipeline at all, regardless of how well-structured its content is.
        </p>

        <h3>AI Crawler Access</h3>
        <p>
          Each major AI platform operates its own crawlers: GPTBot (OpenAI / ChatGPT), PerplexityBot (Perplexity AI), ClaudeBot and Anthropic-AI (Anthropic), Google-Extended (Google AI Overviews), and Bingbot (Microsoft Copilot). When brands updated robots.txt rules in 2023 and 2024 to prevent training-data scraping, many inadvertently blocked the same user-agents from retrieving their content at query time. Audit your robots.txt now and confirm that each crawl-time agent is explicitly allowed.
        </p>

        <h3>The llms.txt Standard</h3>
        <p>
          The <code class="bg-geo-900 text-accent-300 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs border border-geo-700">llms.txt</code> standard is emerging as a way for websites to communicate directly with AI systems — declaring the site's purpose, priority pages, and expertise areas. Analogous to how <code class="bg-geo-900 text-accent-300 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs border border-geo-700">robots.txt</code> governs which pages a crawler may access, <code class="bg-geo-900 text-accent-300 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs border border-geo-700">llms.txt</code> declares what those pages are for and how they should be understood. An accurately maintained <code class="bg-geo-900 text-accent-300 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs border border-geo-700">llms.txt</code> reduces ambiguity during indexation and signals topical authority to the retrieval system before a single query is processed.
        </p>

        <h3>Crawl Budget and Page Accessibility</h3>
        <p>
          AI crawlers, like traditional search crawlers, have limited resources to allocate across your site. Pages buried deep in your architecture, blocked by JavaScript rendering issues, or protected behind login walls will not be crawled consistently. Ensure your most important content pages are linked from the root of your site structure, load cleanly for crawlers without JavaScript dependencies, and appear in your XML sitemap.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Stage 2 -->
      <div class="prose-dark mt-16">
        <h2 id="stage-2-retrieval" class="anchor-top">Stage 2: Semantic Retrieval</h2>
        <p>
          <strong>Semantic retrieval is the stage at which the engine selects candidate documents from its index for a given query — and it uses a fundamentally different selection model to traditional keyword matching.</strong> Where traditional search engines score pages against a list of query keywords, generative retrieval systems use dense vector embeddings to identify semantic similarity between the query and candidate documents. This means a page can be retrieved for a query even if it does not share exact keyword phrasing, provided the underlying meaning is aligned.
        </p>

        <h3>Topical Clustering</h3>
        <p>
          The retrieval system assesses not just individual pages but the topical depth of your domain. A site with a single authoritative page on a subject retrieves less consistently than a site with a cluster of related pages — a hub page addressing the topic comprehensively, linked to multiple supporting pages that explore subtopics in depth. This is the principle behind the ROOT/NODE/SEED architecture used by <a href="/generative-engine-optimisation/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">GEOoptimised's content model</a>: topical clusters tell the retrieval index that your domain is the authoritative source for an entire subject area, not just a single query.
        </p>

        <h3>Entity Clarity at Retrieval</h3>
        <p>
          Retrieval systems resolve entities before scoring relevance. If the engine cannot clearly identify what your brand is, who owns your content, and what expertise area it represents, it deprioritises your pages even when their content is closely relevant to the query. Consistent use of Organisation schema — with <code class="bg-geo-900 text-accent-300 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs border border-geo-700">sameAs</code> links to Wikidata, LinkedIn, and Companies House — establishes the entity context the retrieval system needs to score your pages confidently.
        </p>

        <h3>Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG)</h3>
        <p>
          Platforms like Perplexity and ChatGPT with browsing use retrieval-augmented generation (RAG): rather than relying solely on pre-trained knowledge, they fetch live web content at query time, extract relevant passages, and use those as context for the generated answer. In a RAG system, the retrieval stage is the critical bottleneck. Content that is semantically well-matched to the target query and cleanly structured for extraction enters the context window and influences the generated response. Content that is vague, poorly structured, or topically isolated does not.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Stage 3 -->
      <div class="prose-dark mt-16">
        <h2 id="stage-3-synthesis" class="anchor-top">Stage 3: LLM Synthesis</h2>
        <p>
          <strong>LLM synthesis is the stage at which the language model extracts passages from retrieved documents and assembles them into a coherent, readable answer — and passage extractability is the dominant selection signal.</strong> Not every retrieved document contributes to the final answer. The synthesis process favours passages that are cleanly bounded, directly responsive to the query, and structurally discrete from surrounding content.
        </p>

        <h3>The Declarative Opening Principle</h3>
        <p>
          Empirical analysis of citation patterns across ChatGPT, Perplexity, and Google AI Overviews consistently shows that cited passages disproportionately open with a direct declarative statement that defines or explains the target concept. A paragraph that begins "Generative engine optimisation is the practice of…" is immediately extractable. A paragraph that begins "Many experts believe that…" or "In recent years, there has been growing interest in…" is not — it requires surrounding context to make sense and is harder to attribute to a specific source claim.
        </p>
        <p>
          Every major section of your content should open with a self-contained, 40–100 word declarative statement. This range is not arbitrary: passages below 40 words are often too context-free to be useful to the synthesis model; passages above 100 words are more likely to be paraphrased or partially extracted rather than cited directly.
        </p>

        <h3>Format Matching</h3>
        <p>
          The synthesis model applies format matching alongside content relevance. For a procedural query ("how to implement GEO"), it preferentially extracts from ordered lists. For a definitional query ("what is GEO"), it extracts from concise paragraph openings. For a comparison query ("GEO vs SEO"), it extracts from tables or parallel list structures. Structure your content to match the answer format that the query type demands — the synthesis model reads structure, not just words.
        </p>

        <h3>Single-Concept Paragraphs</h3>
        <p>
          Long, multi-concept paragraphs are difficult to extract cleanly. Write in single-concept units of two to four sentences. Avoid cross-references that require surrounding context: phrases like "as discussed in the previous section" or "building on the above" anchor a passage to its position in the page rather than making it portable. Every paragraph should read coherently in isolation.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Stage 4 -->
      <div class="prose-dark mt-16">
        <h2 id="stage-4-citation" class="anchor-top">Stage 4: Citation Selection</h2>
        <p>
          <strong>Citation selection is the final stage — where the engine decides which sources receive attribution credit for the generated answer — and entity authority is its primary criterion.</strong> Multiple retrieved documents may have contributed passages to the synthesis. The engine selects which sources to cite based on a combination of entity clarity, schema signals, recency, and the uniqueness of the information contributed.
        </p>

        <h3>Entity Authority</h3>
        <p>
          An entity, in this context, is the machine-readable representation of your brand or organisation. If the AI model can resolve your entity clearly — associating your domain with a specific expertise area, a consistent name, and authoritative third-party mentions — it is more likely to attribute citations to you. Entity clarity is built through consistent Organisation schema with <code class="bg-geo-900 text-accent-300 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs border border-geo-700">sameAs</code> links to third-party identifiers, identical entity descriptions across all web properties, and brand mentions in publications that AI training corpora draw from.
        </p>

        <h3>Schema Signals</h3>
        <p>
          Structured data reduces the ambiguity that causes engines to deprioritise sources at citation stage. Article schema confirms the content as a publication from a named author and organisation with a specific publication date. FAQPage schema explicitly maps questions to answers in machine-readable format. BreadcrumbList schema signals topical hierarchy and category membership. Together, these tell the citation engine that this is credible, attributed, structured content — not an anonymous document of uncertain provenance.
        </p>
        <p>
          On every content page published by <a href="/geo-services/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">GEOoptimised</a>, the author and publisher reference the Organisation entity by <code class="bg-geo-900 text-accent-300 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs border border-geo-700">@id</code> rather than re-declaring it inline. This creates a consistent, cross-page entity graph that citation engines can resolve reliably.
        </p>

        <h3>Unique Data and Recency</h3>
        <p>
          When your content contributes a data point, statistic, or claim that cannot be found on competing pages, the engine has no alternative source for that information — it must cite you or omit the claim entirely. Original research, proprietary benchmarks, and specific named examples consistently improve citation rates. Recency is also a measurable signal: AI engines, particularly Perplexity and ChatGPT with browsing, favour sources with current <code class="bg-geo-900 text-accent-300 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs border border-geo-700">dateModified</code> values in schema and a visible "last updated" timestamp on the page.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Optimising Each Stage -->
      <div class="prose-dark mt-16">
        <h2 id="optimising-each-stage" class="anchor-top">Optimising Each Stage of the GEO Pipeline</h2>
        <p>
          <strong>A complete GEO programme applies specific optimisations at each pipeline stage — covering all four is what creates durable, cross-platform citation authority.</strong> The following tactics are sequenced by stage and form the operational basis of any professional <a href="/geo-services/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">GEO implementation</a>.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="mt-8 space-y-4">
        <div class="card p-6">
          <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">Optimise Stage 1 — Crawl &amp; Index</h3>
          <ul class="mt-3 space-y-1.5 text-sm text-ink-300 leading-relaxed list-disc list-inside">
            <li>Audit robots.txt and explicitly allow GPTBot, PerplexityBot, ClaudeBot, Google-Extended, and Bingbot.</li>
            <li>Implement and maintain <code class="bg-geo-900 text-accent-300 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs border border-geo-700">llms.txt</code> with a clear statement of your domain's expertise areas and priority pages.</li>
            <li>Ensure priority content pages are linked from root-level navigation, not buried three or four levels deep.</li>
            <li>Submit an XML sitemap and verify successful crawl in Google Search Console and Bing Webmaster Tools.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="card p-6">
          <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">Optimise Stage 2 — Semantic Retrieval</h3>
          <ul class="mt-3 space-y-1.5 text-sm text-ink-300 leading-relaxed list-disc list-inside">
            <li>Build topical clusters: a ROOT pillar page linking to NODE hub pages, each linking to multiple SEED detail pages.</li>
            <li>Deploy Organisation schema with <code class="bg-geo-900 text-accent-300 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs border border-geo-700">sameAs</code> links to Wikidata, LinkedIn, and other authoritative identifiers.</li>
            <li>Use canonical URLs consistently to prevent the retrieval index splitting authority across duplicate content.</li>
            <li>Write content that addresses related entities and subtopics within each page to increase semantic density.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="card p-6">
          <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">Optimise Stage 3 — LLM Synthesis</h3>
          <ul class="mt-3 space-y-1.5 text-sm text-ink-300 leading-relaxed list-disc list-inside">
            <li>Open every section with a 40–100 word declarative statement that answers the target query without preamble.</li>
            <li>Write in single-concept paragraphs of two to four sentences — one idea, one paragraph.</li>
            <li>Avoid cross-references that require surrounding context ("as noted above", "see previous section").</li>
            <li>Match content format to query type: numbered lists for procedural queries, tables for comparisons, paragraphs for definitions.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="card p-6">
          <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">Optimise Stage 4 — Citation Selection</h3>
          <ul class="mt-3 space-y-1.5 text-sm text-ink-300 leading-relaxed list-disc list-inside">
            <li>Deploy Article or TechArticle schema on every content page, referencing the Organisation entity by <code class="bg-geo-900 text-accent-300 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs border border-geo-700">@id</code> for author and publisher.</li>
            <li>Deploy FAQPage schema on every page with a FAQ section; BreadcrumbList on every non-homepage page.</li>
            <li>Update <code class="bg-geo-900 text-accent-300 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs border border-geo-700">dateModified</code> in schema whenever content is updated — recency is a measurable citation signal.</li>
            <li>Include original data, specific statistics, and named examples that competing pages do not contain.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Platform Differences -->
      <div class="prose-dark mt-16">
        <h2 id="platform-differences" class="anchor-top">How the Pipeline Differs by Platform</h2>
        <p>
          <strong>Every major generative search engine runs the same four-stage pipeline, but the implementation of each stage varies significantly — and a complete GEO programme accounts for these differences.</strong> Optimising for one platform is not sufficient; cross-model citation requires platform-specific awareness layered on top of the universal pipeline model.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="mt-8 overflow-x-auto rounded-xl border hair">
        <table class="w-full text-sm">
          <thead>
            <tr class="border-b hair bg-white/[.03]">
              <th scope="col" class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-white">Platform</th>
              <th scope="col" class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-white">Retrieval Mechanism</th>
              <th scope="col" class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-white">Key GEO Implication</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody class="divide-y divide-[var(--line)]">
            <tr class="transition hover:bg-white/[.02]">
              <td class="px-4 py-3 font-semibold text-white">Google AI Overviews</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300">Organic ranking + Knowledge Graph entity resolution</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300">Strong traditional SEO authority is a prerequisite; entity schema accelerates AI inclusion</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="transition hover:bg-white/[.02]">
              <td class="px-4 py-3 font-semibold text-white">Perplexity</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300">Live RAG — fetches current web sources at query time</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300">Crawlability, fresh dateModified, and short extractable paragraphs are the primary signals</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="transition hover:bg-white/[.02]">
              <td class="px-4 py-3 font-semibold text-white">ChatGPT (browsing)</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300">Training data + optional live web retrieval via Bing</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300">Entity mentions in training corpora and Bing-indexed live content both influence citation</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="transition hover:bg-white/[.02]">
              <td class="px-4 py-3 font-semibold text-white">Microsoft Copilot</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300">Bing index + GPT-4 reasoning layer</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300">Bing Webmaster Tools verification and Bing crawl access materially improve retrieval probability</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="transition hover:bg-white/[.02]">
              <td class="px-4 py-3 font-semibold text-white">Claude (Anthropic)</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300">Training data + optional web search for recent queries</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300">Allow Anthropic-AI and ClaudeBot in robots.txt; entity clarity in schema supports training-data citation</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="transition hover:bg-white/[.02]">
              <td class="px-4 py-3 font-semibold text-white">Gemini</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300">Google index + real-time search integration</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300">Benefits from the same SEO and entity signals as Google AI Overviews; Knowledge Graph presence is key</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <div class="prose-dark mt-8">
        <p>
          Perplexity is the most transparent platform for testing your GEO implementation. Because it is purely RAG-driven with live retrieval, it responds to content changes faster than any other platform. Use Perplexity citation performance as your primary early-stage indicator that extraction architecture is working — if a passage is cited by Perplexity, the structural quality is sufficient for the synthesis stage across other platforms too.
        </p>
        <p>
          For a detailed side-by-side of how generative optimisation compares to traditional search optimisation across dimensions including signals, metrics, and tools, see our <a href="/geo-vs-seo/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">GEO vs SEO guide</a>. For a definition-first introduction to the discipline, see <a href="/what-is-geo/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">what is GEO?</a>
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- FAQ -->
      <div class="prose-dark mt-16">
        <h2 id="faq" class="anchor-top">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      </div>

      <div class="mt-8 space-y-2" id="faq-accordion">
        {faqs.map(faq => (
          <div class="card overflow-hidden">
            <button
              type="button"
              class="flex w-full items-center justify-between p-5 text-left text-sm font-semibold text-white transition hover:bg-white/[.02]"
              aria-expanded="false"
            >
              <span>{faq.q}</span>
              <span class="faq-icon ml-4 shrink-0 text-[var(--accent)] transition-transform duration-200">+</span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-body max-h-0 overflow-hidden transition-[max-height] duration-300 ease-in-out">
              <p class="px-5 pb-5 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">{faq.a}</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>

      <!-- Related Reading -->
      <div class="mt-16" id="related">
        <span class="eyebrow">Related reading</span>
        <div class="mt-6 grid gap-6 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-4">
          {related.map(item => (
            <a href={item.href} class="card card-hover block p-5 no-underline">
              <span class="eyebrow">{item.tag}</span>
              <h3 class="mt-2 font-display text-base font-semibold text-white">{item.title}</h3>
              <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-ink-300">{item.excerpt}</p>
              <span class="mt-3 inline-flex items-center gap-1 text-sm text-[var(--accent)]">Read guide <span aria-hidden="true">&rarr;</span></span>
            </a>
          ))}
        </div>
      </div>

    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- CTA -->
